An article used to connect words, phrases, or clauses representing alternatives; used to connect alternative terms for the same thing; used in correlation; used to correct or rephrase what was previously said; otherwise.
A term referring to the clinical or pathologic observation of a tumor extension from its original site of growth to another anatomic site.

A usually aggressive malignant neoplasm of the soft tissue or bone. It arises from muscle, fat, fibrous tissue, bone, cartilage, and blood vessels. Sarcomas occur in both children and adults. The prognosis depends largely on the degree of differentiation (grade) of the neoplasm. Representative subtypes are liposarcoma, leiomyosarcoma, osteosarcoma, and chondrosarcoma.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: locations or structures in the human body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small, fingerlike pouch that sticks out from the cecum (the first part of the large intestine near the end of the small intestine).

Concepts.definition: Small tissue projection existing as a cecal diverticulum with a questionable history of vestigial versus specialized organ.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A muscular tube that extends from the end of the small intestine to the anus. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: A muscular tube that extends from the end of the small intestine to the anus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the digestive tube between the stomach and the cecum or beginning of the large intestine; it consists of three portions: duodenum, jejunum, and ileum. SYN intestinum tenue.

Concepts.definition: The section of the intestines between the pylorus and cecum. The small intestine is approximately 20 feet long and consists of the duodenum, the jejunum, and the ileum. Its main function is to absorb nutrients from food as the food is transported to the large intestine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The organ located between the esophagus and the small intestine where digestion of food occurs before passing to the small intestine.

Concepts.definition: The primary organ of food digestion. It is located under the diaphragm, between the liver and the spleen as well as between the esophagus and the small intestine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the digestive canal between the pharynx and stomach. It is about 25 cm long and consists of three parts: the cervical part, from the cricoid cartilage to the thoracic inlet; thoracic part, from thoracic inlet to the diaphragm; and abdominal part, below the diaphragm to the cardiac opening of the stomach.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the digestive canal between the pharynx and stomach. It is about 25 cm long and consists of three parts: the cervical part, from the cricoid cartilage to the thoracic inlet; thoracic part, from thoracic inlet to the diaphragm; and abdominal part, below the diaphragm to the cardiac opening of the stomach.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An external male reproductive organ. It contains a tube called the urethra, which carries semen and urine to the outside of the body.

Concepts.definition: The male organ of urination and copulation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The female genital canal, extending from the uterus to the vulva.

Concepts.definition: The female genital canal, extending from the uterus to the vulva.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The external female genital organs, including the clitoris, vaginal lips, and the opening to the vagina.

Concepts.definition: The external, visible part of the female genitalia surrounding the urethral and vaginal opening. The vulva includes the clitoris and inner as well as outer labia.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The erectile tissue in the vulva. It is composed of the corpora cavernosa and the glans clitoris.

Concepts.definition: The erectile tissue in the vulva. It is composed of the corpora cavernosa and the glans clitoris.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the paired female reproductive glands containing the ova or germ cells; the ovary's stroma is a vascular connective tissue containing numbers of ovarian follicles enclosing the ova; surrounding this stroma is a more condensed layer of stroma called the tunica albuginea.

Concepts.definition: One of the paired female reproductive glands containing the ova or germ cells; the ovary's stroma is a vascular connective tissue containing numbers of ovarian follicles enclosing the ova.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The hollow muscular organ in which the impregnated ovum is developed into the child; it is about 7.5 cm in length in the nonpregnant woman, and consists of a main portion (body) with an elongated lower part (neck), at the extremity of which is the opening (os). The upper rounded portion of the uterus, opposite the os, is the fundus, at each extremity of which is the horn marking the part where the uterine tube joins the uterus and through which the ovum reaches the uterine cavity after leaving the ovary. The organ is supported in the pelvic cavity by the broad ligaments, round ligaments, cardinal ligaments, and rectouterine and vesicouterine folds or ligaments. SYN metra, womb.

Concepts.definition: A hollow, thick-walled, muscular organ located within the pelvic cavity of a woman. Within the uterus the fertilized egg implants and the fetus develops during pregnancy.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The walnut shaped accessory sex gland of the male reproductive system. It is located in the pelvis just below the bladder, surrounding the prostatic part of the urethra. The prostate gland secretes a fluid which is part of the semen.

Concepts.definition: The walnut shaped accessory sex gland of the male reproductive system. It is located in the pelvis just below the bladder, surrounding the prostatic part of the urethra. The prostate gland secretes a fluid which is part of the semen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Either of the paired male reproductive glands that produce the male germ cells and the male hormones.

Concepts.definition: Either of the paired male reproductive glands that produce the male germ cells and the male hormones.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A distensible musculomembranous organ serving as a receptacle for fluid, as the gallbladder.

Concepts.definition: The distensible sac-like organ that functions as a reservoir of urine, collecting from the kidneys and eliminating via the urethra.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the two organs that excrete the urine. The kidneys are bean-shaped organs (about 11 cm long, 5 cm wide, and 3 cm thick) lying on either side of the vertebral column, posterior to the peritoneum, about opposite the twelfth thoracic and first three lumbar vertebrae. SYN ren, nephros.

Concepts.definition: One of the two bean-shaped organs located on each side of the spine in the retroperitoneum. The right kidney is located below the liver and the left kidney below the diaphragm. The kidneys filter and secrete metabolic products and minerals from the blood, thus maintaining homeostasis. On the superior pole of each kidney there is an adrenal gland. Each kidney and adrenal gland is surrounded by fat.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Paired glands situated in the retroperitoneal tissues at the superior pole of each kidney.

Concepts.definition: A flattened, roughly triangular body resting upon the upper end of each kidney; it is one of the ductless glands furnishing internal secretions (epinephrine and norepinephrine from the medulla and steroid hormones from the cortex).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The soft, sponge-like tissue in the center of bones that produces white blood cells, red blood cells, and platelets.

Concepts.definition: The tissue occupying the spaces of bone. It consists of blood vessel sinuses and a network of hematopoietic cells which give rise to the red cells, white cells, and megakaryocytes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rounded mass of lymphatic tissue that is surrounded by a capsule of connective tissue. Lymph glands filter lymph (lymphatic fluid), and they store lymphocytes (white blood cells). They are located along lymphatic vessels. Also called a lymph node.

Concepts.definition: A bean-shaped organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is part of the lymphatic system and is found throughout the body. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and its main function is immune protection.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An organ that is part of the lymphatic system. The spleen produces lymphocytes, filters the blood, stores blood cells, and destroys old blood cells. It is located on the left side of the abdomen near the stomach.

Concepts.definition: An organ that is part of the hematopoietic and immune systems. It is composed of the white pulp and the red pulp and is surrounded by a capsule. It is located in the left hypochondriac region. Its functions include lymphocyte production, blood cell storage, and blood cell destruction.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: 1. An organ and the enveloping membrane of the body; includes, in addition to the epidermis and dermis, all of the derivatives of the epidermis, e.g., hairs, nails, sudoriferous and sebaceous glands, and mammary glands. Subdivisions of the skin surround various body parts; as a whole, the skin constitutes the external surface of the body. 2. The rind, capsule, or covering of any body or part.

Concepts.definition: An organ that constitutes the external surface of the body. It consists of the epidermis, dermis, and skin appendages.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid that is ordinarily present in the pleural space. It allows for normal movement of the lungs during respiration.

Concepts.definition: The fluid that is ordinarily present in the pleural space. It allows for normal movement of the lungs during respiration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Accumulation of fluid in the peritoneal cavity.  The fluid may be serous, hemorrhagic, or the result of tumor metastasis to the peritoneum. -- 2004

Concepts.definition: The accumulation of fluid in the peritoneal cavity, which may be serous, hemorrhagic, or the result of tumor metastasis to the peritoneum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The organ of sight or vision. (On-line Medical Dictionary): An article which expresses the relation of connection or addition. It is used to conjoin a word with a word, a clause with a clause, or a sentence with a sentence.: The bony cavity of the skull which contains the eye, anterior portion of the optic nerve, ocular muscles and ocular adnexa.  Seven bones contribute to the structure of the orbit: the frontal, maxillary, zygomatic, sphenoid, lacrimal, ethmoid, and palatine bones.

Concepts.definition: The organ of sight or vision.
An article which expresses the relation of connection or addition. It is used to conjoin a word with a word, a clause with a clause, or a sentence with a sentence.

The bony cavity of the skull which contains the eye, anterior portion of the optic nerve, ocular muscles and ocular adnexa. Seven bones contribute to the structure of the orbit: the frontal, maxillary, zygomatic, sphenoid, lacrimal, ethmoid, and palatine bones.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The main information-processing organs of the nervous system, consisting of the brain, spinal cord, and meninges.

Concepts.definition: The part of the nervous system that consists of the brain, spinal cord, and meninges.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of a pair of viscera occupying the pulmonary cavities of the thorax, the organs of respiration in which aeration of the blood takes place. As a rule, the right lung is slightly larger than the left and is divided into three lobes (an upper, a middle, and a lower or basal), while the left has but two lobes (an upper and a lower or basal). Each lung is irregularly conical in shape, presenting a blunt upper extremity (the apex), a concave base following the curve of the diaphragm, an outer convex surface (costal surface), an inner or mediastinal surface (mediastinal surface), a thin and sharp anterior border, and a thick and rounded posterior border. SYN pulmo.

Concepts.definition: One of a pair of viscera occupying the pulmonary cavities of the thorax, the organs of respiration in which aeration of the blood takes place. As a rule, the right lung is slightly larger than the left and is divided into three lobes (an upper, a middle, and a lower or basal), while the left has two lobes (an upper and a lower or basal). Each lung is irregularly conical in shape, presenting a blunt upper extremity (the apex), a concave base following the curve of the diaphragm, an outer convex surface (costal surface), an inner or mediastinal surface (mediastinal surface), a thin and sharp anterior border, and a thick and rounded posterior border.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A large organ located in the upper abdomen. The liver cleanses the blood and aids in digestion by secreting bile.

Concepts.definition: A triangular-shaped organ located under the diaphragm in the right hypochondrium. It is the largest internal organ of the body, weighting up to 2 kg. Metabolism and bile secretion are its main functions. It is composed of cells which have the ability to regenerate.

ValueMeaning.administrativeNotes: 2023.3.7 Alt VM added per ticket request CADSR0002119. ak

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A non-encapsulated elongated and lobulated organ, extending from the concavity of the duodenum to the spleen; it consists of a head, an elongated body, and a tail. It contains two functional components: an exocrine component that secretes juices into the intestine and an endocrine component that secretes hormones (insulin and glucagon).

Concepts.definition: An organ behind the lower part of the stomach that is the shape of a fish and about the size of a hand. It is a compound gland composed of both exocrine and endocrine tissues. The endocrine pancreas makes insulin so that the body can use glucose (sugar) for energy. The exocrine pancreas makes enzymes that help the body digest food. Spread all over the pancreas are areas called the Islets of Langerhans. The cells in these areas each have a special purpose. The alpha cells make glucagon, which raises the level of glucose in the blood; the beta cells make insulin; the delta cells make somatostatin. There are also PP cells and D1 cells, about which little is known.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (PLOOR-a) A thin layer of tissue covering the lungs and the wall of the chest cavity to protect and cushion the lungs. A small amount of fluid that acts as a lubricant allows the lungs to move smoothly in the chest cavity during breathing.

Concepts.definition: The tissue that lines the wall of the thoracic cavity and the surface of the lungs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (PAIR-ih-toe-NEE-um) The tissue that lines the abdominal wall and covers most of the organs in the abdomen.

Concepts.definition: The tissue that lines the wall of the abdominal cavity, intestine, mesentery, and pelvic organs. It consists of the parietal peritoneum and the visceral peritoneum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fibroserous sac surrounding the heart and the roots of the great vessels.

Concepts.definition: A conical membranous sac filled with serous fluid in which the heart as well as the roots of the aorta and other large blood vessels are contained.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Within the abdomen.

Concepts.definition: Within the abdomen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The back of the abdomen where the kidneys lie and the great blood vessels run.

Concepts.definition: The back of the abdomen where the kidneys lie and the great blood vessels run.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The region of the body between the neck and the upper arm.

Concepts.definition: The region of the body between the neck and the upper arm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of two hemispheric projections of variable size situated in the subcutaneous layer over the pectoralis major muscle on either side of the chest.

Concepts.definition: One of two hemispheric projections of variable size situated in the subcutaneous layer over the pectoralis major muscle on either side of the chest.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (mee-dee-a-STYE-num) The area between the lungs. The organs in this area include the heart and its large blood vessels, the trachea, the esophagus, the bronchi, and lymph nodes.

Concepts.definition: An anatomic site along the midline and under the sternum that contains the heart and pericardium, the bases of the great vessels, the trachea and bronchi, esophagus, thymus, lymph nodes, thoracic duct, phrenic and vagus nerves, and other structures and tissues.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The region on either side of the body that extends from the last rib to the hip.

Concepts.definition: The region on either side of the body that extends from the last rib to the hip.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The oblique anatomic tunnel in the anterior lower abdomen.  In males it conveys the spermatic cord structures and is the passage through which the testes descend into the scrotum; in females it conveys the round ligament.

Concepts.definition: The oblique anatomic tunnel in the anterior lower abdomen. In males it conveys the spermatic cord structures and is the passage through which the testes descend into the scrotum; in females it conveys the round ligament.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Of, or related to, the structures proximal to the meninges.

Concepts.definition: Of, or related to, the structures proximal to meninges.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The soft tissues in close proximity to the testis.

Concepts.definition: The soft tissues in close proximity to the testis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Either of the two bones (left and right) that form the front of the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: Either of the two bones (left and right) that form the front of the pelvis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The body excluding the head and neck and limbs.

Concepts.definition: The body excluding the head and neck and limbs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The irregular and largest bone that forms the heel.

Concepts.definition: The irregular and largest tarsal bone that forms the heel.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The superficial areas of head and neck including the oral cavity, buccal mucosa, and the parotid region.

Concepts.definition: The superficial areas of head and neck including the oral cavity, buccal mucosa, and the parotid region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bone in the fingers or toes.

Concepts.definition: A bone in the fingers or toes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The posterior aspect of the lower extremity that extends from the knee to the foot.

Concepts.definition: The posterior aspect of the lower extremity that extends from the knee to the foot.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The most posterior and ventral bone making up the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: The most posterior and ventral bone making up the pelvis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the ring-shaped bony structures that constitute the spinal column and surround the spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: Any of thirty-three ring-shaped structures that form the vertebral column which surrounds and protects the spinal cord. Each vertebra consists of a bony body with its superior and inferior articular surfaces covered by hyaline cartilage. The body includes the centrum anteriorly and vertebral arch posteriorly. The articular surfaces of the vertebrae are connected by a fibrocartilaginous intervertebral disc.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The tissues that surround the organs that are present within the abdominal cavity. The abdominal wall tissue is composed of layers of fat, parietal peritoneum, fascia, and muscles.

Concepts.definition: The tissues that surround the organs that are present within the abdominal cavity. The abdominal wall tissue is composed of layers of fat, parietal peritoneum, fascia, and muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The total system of structures outside the lungs that move as a part of breathing; it includes all structures from the skin to the parietal pleura.

Concepts.definition: The total system of structures outside the lungs that move as a part of breathing; it includes all structures from the skin to the parietal pleura.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The distal portion of the upper extremity. It consists of the carpus, metacarpus, and digits.

Concepts.definition: The distal portion of the upper extremity. It consists of the carpus, metacarpus, and digits.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The structure found below the ankle joint required for locomotion.

Concepts.definition: The structure found below the ankle joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Commonly used to refer to the whole lower limb but technically only the part between the knee and ankle.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the lower extremity between the knee and the ankle. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole inferior limb.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The bone of the foot that connects with the tibia and fibula to form the ankle joint. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: The bone of the foot that connects with the tibia and fibula to form the ankle joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The wedge-shaped bone consisting of five fused vertebrae, S1-S5 in man, forming the posterior part of the pelvis; its base connects with the lowest lumbar vertebra and its tip with the coccyx.

Concepts.definition: The triangular bone, made up of 5 fused bones of the spine, located in the lower area of the spine between the fifth lumbar vertebra and the coccyx.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the elbow. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole superior limb.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the elbow. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole superior limb.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bone belonging to the middle part of the foot located between toes and ankle. There are 5 metatarsal bones and they are numbered from the medial side.

Concepts.definition: A bone belonging to the middle part of the foot located between toes and ankle. There are 5 metatarsal bones and they are numbered from the medial side.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Either of the fleshy mounds in the rear pelvic area of the human body formed by the gluteal muscles.

Concepts.definition: Either of the fleshy mounds in the rear pelvic area of the human body formed by the gluteal muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The bone of the lower leg lateral to and smaller than the tibia. In proportion to its length, it is the most slender of the long bones.

Concepts.definition: The small, lateral calf bone extending from the knee to the ankle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The second longest bone of the skeleton. It is located on the medial side of the lower leg, articulating with the FIBULA laterally, the TALUS distally, and the FEMUR proximally.

Concepts.definition: A bone located between the femur and the tarsus, being part of the lower leg.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The longest and largest bone of the skeleton, it is situated between the hip and the knee.

Concepts.definition: The upper leg bone positioned between the pelvis and the knee.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the bones that comprise the forearm. The largest aspect articulates with the humerus at the elbow joint and the smallest portion of the ulna articulates with the carpal bones in the wrist.

Concepts.definition: One of the bones that comprise the forearm. The largest aspect articulates with the humerus at the elbow joint and the smallest portion of the ulna articulates with the carpal bones in the wrist.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The long bone of the forearm that extends from the lateral aspect of the elbow to the thumb-side of the wrist.

Concepts.definition: The long bone of the forearm that extends from the lateral aspect of the elbow to the thumb-side of the wrist.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The structure on the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist.

Concepts.definition: The structure on the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bone of the upper extremity that articulates with the acromion process of the scapula on one end and the sternum on the other.

Concepts.definition: One of a pair of bones linking the scapula and the sternum. The clavicle is part of the pectoral girdle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The upper arm bone between the shoulder and elbow.

Concepts.definition: The upper arm bone between the shoulder and elbow.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The upper jawbone in vertebrates: it is fused to the cranium.

Concepts.definition: The upper jawbone in vertebrates; it is fused to the cranium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The largest and strongest bone of the FACE constituting the lower jaw. It supports the lower teeth.

Concepts.definition: The lower jaw bone holding the lower teeth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The skeleton of the head including the bones of the face and the bones enclosing the brain.

Concepts.definition: The bones that form the head, made up of the bones of the braincase and face.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small flat triangular bone in front of the knee that articulates with the femur and protects the knee joint.

Concepts.definition: A small flat triangular bone in front of the knee that articulates with the femur and protects the knee joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The broad, dorsal, upper, and widest of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: The broad, dorsal, upper, and widest of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the five bones between the wrist and the fingers that form the skeleton of the palm.

Concepts.definition: Any of the five bones between the wrist and the fingers that form the skeleton of the palm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any one of the paired bones, 12 on either side, extending from the thoracic vertebrae toward the median line on the ventral aspect of the trunk. The long curved bones which form the rib cage. Generally, ribs 1 to 7 are connected to the sternum' by their costal cartilages and are called true ribs, whereas ribs 8 to 12 are termed false ribs.

Concepts.definition: Any one of the paired bones, 12 on either side, extending from the thoracic vertebrae toward the median line on the ventral aspect of the trunk. The long curved bones which form the rib cage. Generally, ribs 1 to 7 are connected to the sternum by their costal cartilages and are called true ribs, whereas ribs 8 to 12 are termed false ribs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The flat triangle-shaped bone that connects the humerus with the clavicle in the back of the shoulder.

Concepts.definition: The flat triangle-shaped bone that connects the humerus with the clavicle in the back of the shoulder.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The long, flat bone connecting with the cartilages of the first seven ribs and the clavicle.

Concepts.definition: The long, flat bone connecting with the cartilages of the first seven ribs and the clavicle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A part of the lower limb, located between hip and knee.

Concepts.definition: A part of the lower limb, located between hip and knee.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A gliding joint between the distal ends of the tibia and fibula and the proximal end of the talus.

Concepts.definition: The glandular portion of the salivary system whose combined secretions constitute the saliva; a clear, alkaline, somewhat viscus secretion that keeps the mouth moist and aids in swallowing and digesting food. It includes the major salivary glands - sublingual, submandibular, and parotid glands, as well as numerous minor glands.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A hinge joint in the human leg connecting the tibia and fibula with the femur and protected in front by the patella.

Concepts.definition: A joint connecting the lower part of the femur with the upper part of the tibia. The lower part of the femur and the upper part of the tibia are attached to each other by ligaments. Other structures of the knee joint include the upper part of the fibula, located below and parallel to the tibia, and the patella which moves as the knee bends.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A ball-and-socket joint between the head of the femur and the acetabulum.

Concepts.definition: A ball-and-socket joint between the head of the femur and the acetabulum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A joint between the distal end of the radius and the proximal row of carpal bones.

Concepts.definition: A joint between the distal end of the radius and the proximal row of carpal bones.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The bony, basin-shaped structure formed by the hipbones and the base of the backbone supporting the lower limbs in humans.

Concepts.definition: The bony, basin-shaped structure formed by the hipbones and the base of the backbone supporting the lower limbs in humans.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The hinge joint between the forearm and upper arm or the corresponding joint in the forelimb of a quadruped.

Concepts.definition: A type of hinge joint located between the forearm and upper arm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Higher in place or position; the topmost one of two.: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the elbow. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole superior limb.

Concepts.definition: Higher in place or position; the topmost one of two.
The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the elbow. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole superior limb.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The structure on the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist.

Concepts.definition: The structure on the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The soft internal organs of the body, including the lungs, the heart, and the organs of the digestive, excretory, and reproductive systems.

Concepts.definition: Two or more internal organs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Within the spine (backbone).

Concepts.definition: Within the spine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Pertaining to muscles and/or tissue adjacent to the spinal column.

Concepts.definition: Pertaining to muscles and/or tissue adjacent to the spinal column.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Denoting the back surface of the body; at or near the hind end in quadrupeds or toward the spine in primates.: The total system of structures outside the lungs that move as a part of breathing; it includes all structures from the skin to the parietal pleura.

Concepts.definition: Denoting the back surface of the body; at or near the hind end in quadrupeds or toward the spine in primates.
The total system of structures outside the lungs that move as a part of breathing; it includes all structures from the skin to the parietal pleura.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Denoting the front surface of the body; often used to indicate the position of one structure relative to another.: The total system of structures outside the lungs that move as a part of breathing; it includes all structures from the skin to the parietal pleura.

Concepts.definition: Denoting the front surface of the body; often used to indicate the position of one structure relative to another.
The total system of structures outside the lungs that move as a part of breathing; it includes all structures from the skin to the parietal pleura.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: locations or structures in the human body.

RepresentationTerm.preferredDefinition: A usually aggressive malignant mesenchymal cell tumor most commonly arising from muscle, fat, fibrous tissue, bone, cartilage, and blood vessels.  Sarcomas occur in both children and adults.  The prognosis depends largely on the degree of differentiation (grade) of the tumor.  Representative subtypes are liposarcoma, leiomyosarcoma, osteosarcoma, and chondrosarcoma. -- 2004:Named locations of, or within, the body.

Concepts.definition: A usually aggressive malignant neoplasm of the soft tissue or bone. It arises from muscle, fat, fibrous tissue, bone, cartilage, and blood vessels. Sarcomas occur in both children and adults. The prognosis depends largely on the degree of differentiation (grade) of the neoplasm. Representative subtypes are liposarcoma, leiomyosarcoma, osteosarcoma, and chondrosarcoma.
